New York City FC-- everyone

00:00:11.740 --> 00:00:14.300
please give a warm welcome
to Mr. Patrick Vieira.

00:00:14.300 --> 00:00:16.800
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:16.800 --> 00:00:20.680
 

00:00:20.680 --> 00:00:22.090
Pleasure to have you.

00:00:22.090 --> 00:00:28.090
 

00:00:28.090 --> 00:00:29.537
Patrick, welcome to Google.

00:00:29.537 --> 00:00:30.620
PATRICK VIEIRA: Thank you.

00:00:30.620 --> 00:00:31.453
Thank you very much.

00:00:31.453 --> 00:00:33.130
Good afternoon.

00:00:33.130 --> 00:00:34.695
I was quite really
excited to come

00:00:34.695 --> 00:00:37.950
to Google-- a little bit
less now, because I seen too

00:00:37.950 --> 00:00:39.775
many Red Bulls shirts.

00:00:39.775 --> 00:00:41.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:41.270 --> 00:00:42.347
 

00:00:42.347 --> 00:00:44.680
But the good thing is that
they are sitting at the back.

00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:45.180
So it's OK.

00:00:45.180 --> 00:00:46.620
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:46.620 --> 00:00:46.642
 

00:00:46.642 --> 00:00:48.100
JON JAKLITSCH: So
Patrick, I think

00:00:48.100 --> 00:00:51.490
there's a lot of interest
here about your playing career

00:00:51.490 --> 00:00:54.480
and also about your
transition to being a manager.

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:58.010
But I thought we'd start off
to talk about your early years.

00:00:58.010 --> 00:01:01.700
Can you tell us, how did
you first get into football?

00:01:01.700 --> 00:01:03.870
PATRICK VIEIRA: Football
always been part of my life

00:01:03.870 --> 00:01:06.350
since I was seven,
eight years old.

00:01:06.350 --> 00:01:08.600
I grew up in Senegal.

00:01:08.600 --> 00:01:10.520
And from Senegal,
we moved to Paris

00:01:10.520 --> 00:01:12.500
when I was eight,
nine years old.

00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:19.910
And honestly, football
was and still a easy way

00:01:19.910 --> 00:01:21.880
to get out of poverty.

00:01:21.880 --> 00:01:30.190
And growing up with cousins,
uncles, brothers, life

00:01:30.190 --> 00:01:31.950
wasn't that simple.

00:01:31.950 --> 00:01:36.520
But we always managed
to get what we needed.

00:01:36.520 --> 00:01:42.350
And growing up, find out that I
had a small talent in football.

00:01:42.350 --> 00:01:47.740
And I was more concentrate
on the sports side

00:01:47.740 --> 00:01:51.110
than on the academic side of it.

00:01:51.110 --> 00:01:57.410
And I wanted to use a talent
to really do something

00:01:57.410 --> 00:01:59.330
really interesting, and
something that I love,

00:01:59.330 --> 00:02:03.970
and something that will help my
family to have a better life.

00:02:03.970 --> 00:02:05.590
And I was quite, quite lucky.

00:02:05.590 --> 00:02:09.900
Because every year that I was
involved in the football club,

00:02:09.900 --> 00:02:16.010
I always had somebody to support
me, somebody to guide me,

00:02:16.010 --> 00:02:21.000
to make me realize how important
it is, to make a sacrifice.

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:25.740
And those peoples really
contribute massively

00:02:25.740 --> 00:02:27.952
on who I am today.

00:02:27.952 --> 00:02:30.410
JON JAKLITSCH: Can you tell
us more about your role models

00:02:30.410 --> 00:02:31.340
growing up?

00:02:31.340 --> 00:02:34.870
PATRICK VIEIRA: But when I
grew up in France in '84,

00:02:34.870 --> 00:02:37.960
you had a really
successful national team.

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:40.685
We used to call them
the [SPEAKING FRENCH].

00:02:40.685 --> 00:02:42.560
I think the French people
who are in the room

00:02:42.560 --> 00:02:44.860
will know who I
am talking about.

00:02:44.860 --> 00:02:49.130
We had the players like
Platini, Tigana, Alain Giresse,

00:02:49.130 --> 00:02:51.000
and Luis Fernandez.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:54.130
There were the heart of
the French National Team

00:02:54.130 --> 00:02:55.140
at that period.

00:02:55.140 --> 00:02:57.900
And Luis Fernandez, who
was an example for me,

00:02:57.900 --> 00:03:00.360
because he was playing
in the same position.

00:03:00.360 --> 00:03:02.430
And he was an idol.

00:03:02.430 --> 00:03:05.972
He was somebody that
I was looking up.

00:03:05.972 --> 00:03:07.680
And I was really lucky,
because I had him

00:03:07.680 --> 00:03:09.490
as a manager when
I was in Cannes.

00:03:09.490 --> 00:03:15.360
And he was the coach that
made me play my first game

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:16.963
in the professional level.

00:03:16.963 --> 00:03:20.120
JON JAKLITSCH:
That's great, Patrick.

00:03:20.120 --> 00:03:23.990
Switching now into your
professional career,

00:03:23.990 --> 00:03:27.480
you've had a lot of great
achievements in your career.

00:03:27.480 --> 00:03:30.017
What would you
rank, looking back,

00:03:30.017 --> 00:03:31.350
as the one you're most proud of?

00:03:31.350 --> 00:03:34.125
 

00:03:34.125 --> 00:03:35.750
PATRICK VIEIRA: I've
been really lucky,

00:03:35.750 --> 00:03:39.490
because I achieve more than
what I was dreaming of.

00:03:39.490 --> 00:03:43.350
And I've been really
successful, because I

00:03:43.350 --> 00:03:47.710
was at the right place
at the right time.

00:03:47.710 --> 00:03:50.860
I make the right decision
at the right time,

00:03:50.860 --> 00:03:56.900
because when I was 17, the
club that I was playing for

00:03:56.900 --> 00:03:58.732
went into a bankrupt.

00:03:58.732 --> 00:04:00.440
And when the club's
going into a bankrupt

00:04:00.440 --> 00:04:04.020
we became a free agent, so
I had different options.

00:04:04.020 --> 00:04:08.130
And I was really lucky to
make the right choices.

00:04:08.130 --> 00:04:12.170
Because that choices
helped me to grow up,

00:04:12.170 --> 00:04:15.540
and to improve myself,
and to be a better player.

00:04:15.540 --> 00:04:22.350
But you know, what is
important is that football

00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:24.040
was and still a big passion.

00:04:24.040 --> 00:04:25.830
And I fell in love
with the game.

00:04:25.830 --> 00:04:28.310
And even today, it is a passion.

00:04:28.310 --> 00:04:31.740
And it is a love for the game.

00:04:31.740 --> 00:04:34.910
But to answer your
question that I forget--

00:04:34.910 --> 00:04:36.330
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:36.330 --> 00:04:37.830
JON JAKLITSCH:
So accomplishment

00:04:37.830 --> 00:04:39.900
that you're most proud
of in your career?

00:04:39.900 --> 00:04:42.250
PATRICK VIEIRA:
But you know what?

00:04:42.250 --> 00:04:45.220
Winning the World Cup in '98
with the French National Team

00:04:45.220 --> 00:04:47.050
is a big, big achievement.

00:04:47.050 --> 00:04:51.840
Because we won the
World Cup in France.

00:04:51.840 --> 00:04:55.410
And at that time,
France was going

00:04:55.410 --> 00:04:57.256
through a really
difficult period

00:04:57.256 --> 00:05:02.540
of crisis-- identity, racism.

00:05:02.540 --> 00:05:04.582
So to win the World
Cup, I think we

00:05:04.582 --> 00:05:05.790
send a really strong message.

00:05:05.790 --> 00:05:08.880
Because that period,
the French National Team

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:12.290
had a massive reflect
on the society.

00:05:12.290 --> 00:05:14.830
The diversity of the
French national team

00:05:14.830 --> 00:05:17.890
was the French society.

00:05:17.890 --> 00:05:23.030
So it was really strong message
that we sent to the world.

00:05:23.030 --> 00:05:26.340
And that was a really
proud moment for me

00:05:26.340 --> 00:05:28.200
to be part of that team.

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:31.660
And of course, signing my
first professional contract

00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:36.235
was a massive
success, because that

00:05:36.235 --> 00:05:40.360
is what I was dreaming about
since I was eight years old.

00:05:40.360 --> 00:05:42.956
And of course, going
through with Arsenal

00:05:42.956 --> 00:05:47.150
through a season unbeaten
was a good achievement.

00:05:47.150 --> 00:05:52.840
And being coach as well, because
during my playing career,

00:05:52.840 --> 00:05:55.316
being a coach wasn't
part of my plan.

00:05:55.316 --> 00:05:56.690
If you was asking
me, do you want

00:05:56.690 --> 00:05:59.430
to be a coach when you retired,
I would said, no chance.

00:05:59.430 --> 00:06:00.440
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:00.440 --> 00:06:04.190
And just life is
full of surprising.

00:06:04.190 --> 00:06:06.770
JON JAKLITSCH: Tell me
more about the World Cup

00:06:06.770 --> 00:06:08.950
when you won in France in '98.

00:06:08.950 --> 00:06:13.500
What do you remember most
about what happened afterwards?

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:16.002
How did it change your life?

00:06:16.002 --> 00:06:17.460
PATRICK VIEIRA: It
changed my life,

00:06:17.460 --> 00:06:21.200
because that put me there
with the rest of the players

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:23.600
in the international level.

00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:26.600
Winning the World Cup
WITH the team that we had

00:06:26.600 --> 00:06:28.870
was unbelievable.

00:06:28.870 --> 00:06:31.450
I don't think the
French National Team

00:06:31.450 --> 00:06:34.530
will have the team that we had.

00:06:34.530 --> 00:06:37.460
Because that team
was unbelievable.

00:06:37.460 --> 00:06:42.700
We had the best player in
the world of Zinedine Zidane.

00:06:42.700 --> 00:06:44.520
We had one of the
best goalkeeper

00:06:44.520 --> 00:06:46.770
at the time with Fabien Barthez.

00:06:46.770 --> 00:06:50.130
We had one of the best
defender in the world

00:06:50.130 --> 00:06:54.970
with Marcel Desailly, the best
outside back with Lizarazu

00:06:54.970 --> 00:06:57.660
and Lilliam Thuram.

00:06:57.660 --> 00:07:01.496
And just those player
was unbelievable.

00:07:01.496 --> 00:07:02.870
And that time, we
had everything.

00:07:02.870 --> 00:07:04.450
We had talent.

00:07:04.450 --> 00:07:06.710
We had experience.

00:07:06.710 --> 00:07:09.750
We had desire to compete.

00:07:09.750 --> 00:07:12.090
Everything was there
to win the World Cup.

00:07:12.090 --> 00:07:15.162
And to do it in France was
a fantastic achievement.

00:07:15.162 --> 00:07:16.370
JON JAKLITSCH: That's great.

00:07:16.370 --> 00:07:17.250
That's great.

00:07:17.250 --> 00:07:20.080
And you talked a little bit
about your unbeaten season

00:07:20.080 --> 00:07:21.210
at Arsenal.

00:07:21.210 --> 00:07:23.780
Looking back on that
season, is there

00:07:23.780 --> 00:07:26.870
any particular moment
you remember most

00:07:26.870 --> 00:07:30.601
from that season, maybe a time
where you thought, you know,

00:07:30.601 --> 00:07:32.850
oh, this is the end, it's
not gonna to happen anymore,

00:07:32.850 --> 00:07:37.300
or this was my favorite
moment from that season?

00:07:37.300 --> 00:07:40.930
PATRICK VIEIRA: It's really
difficult to pick up a moment.

00:07:40.930 --> 00:07:42.480
But what I would
during the season

00:07:42.480 --> 00:07:48.790
is that we knew
that was our moment.

00:07:48.790 --> 00:07:52.160
Because every time we went
through a difficult period,

00:07:52.160 --> 00:07:54.710
it was somebody was doing
something different.

00:07:54.710 --> 00:07:56.770
It was Dennis Bergkamp
was doing something

00:07:56.770 --> 00:07:59.390
that was unbelievable.

00:07:59.390 --> 00:08:02.380
It was Thierry Henry was going
to score the goal by himself.

00:08:02.380 --> 00:08:04.890
It was Robert Pires
was making a good play.

00:08:04.890 --> 00:08:07.810
It was the goal keeper was
making an unbelievable save.

00:08:07.810 --> 00:08:10.220
We was going losing
two-nil at half time.

00:08:10.220 --> 00:08:15.010
And we will manage to get back,
because we had the spirit.

00:08:15.010 --> 00:08:17.270
We had the quality up
front to score the goal,

00:08:17.270 --> 00:08:19.470
so not to concede the goal.

00:08:19.470 --> 00:08:22.000
But I think that generation
was really complete,

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:28.040
because in every line,
we had leadership.

00:08:28.040 --> 00:08:30.900
We had talent.

00:08:30.900 --> 00:08:35.350
And we had, for me, what
was really important,

00:08:35.350 --> 00:08:36.829
the same goal, the common goal.

00:08:36.829 --> 00:08:37.620
JON JAKLITSCH: Mm.

00:08:37.620 --> 00:08:40.000
PATRICK VIEIRA: And
that was fantastic.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:42.010
And of course, the
relationship between us

00:08:42.010 --> 00:08:45.372
as well was really good.

00:08:45.372 --> 00:08:46.581
It's a really special moment.

00:08:46.581 --> 00:08:48.955
That's what I was saying early
on that I was quite really

00:08:48.955 --> 00:08:49.560
lucky.

00:08:49.560 --> 00:08:55.920
Because I really play for teams
where we had talents, yes,

00:08:55.920 --> 00:08:59.626
but where we really live
together really well.

00:08:59.626 --> 00:09:03.150
Because to achieve, or to
win something, or to do well,

00:09:03.150 --> 00:09:04.990
you need more than a talent.

00:09:04.990 --> 00:09:07.570
And at Arsenal, at
Juventus, or even

00:09:07.570 --> 00:09:10.030
with the French National Team,
we had more than the talent.

00:09:10.030 --> 00:09:12.430
And this is the reason why
we have been successful.

00:09:12.430 --> 00:09:14.596
JON JAKLITSCH: I've heard
you talk a lot about what

00:09:14.596 --> 00:09:16.180
makes a great team.

00:09:16.180 --> 00:09:19.470
I've heard you say that it's not
necessarily having, you know,

00:09:19.470 --> 00:09:21.810
a great player and
then not caring

00:09:21.810 --> 00:09:25.020
about let's say the goalkeeper
or the defenders, right?

00:09:25.020 --> 00:09:28.619
It's having balance
within a team.

00:09:28.619 --> 00:09:30.160
Would you say that
was something that

00:09:30.160 --> 00:09:32.380
was very common in the
best teams that you played?

00:09:32.380 --> 00:09:32.810
PATRICK VIEIRA: Yes, yes.

00:09:32.810 --> 00:09:33.700
It was really common.

00:09:33.700 --> 00:09:36.230
Because what was
really important for us

00:09:36.230 --> 00:09:38.660
is to understand what
is your strength,

00:09:38.660 --> 00:09:43.410
and what can you do
to help the team?

00:09:43.410 --> 00:09:46.646
Like myself, if I was trying
to be Zinedine Zidane,

00:09:46.646 --> 00:09:48.146
we never going to
win the World Cup.

00:09:48.146 --> 00:09:49.415
[LAUGHTER]

00:09:49.415 --> 00:09:55.520
If you build a team to
have 11 Zinedine Zidane,

00:09:55.520 --> 00:09:57.550
you're will not going
to win the World Cup.

00:09:57.550 --> 00:10:00.230
I think you will need to
mix the team regarding

00:10:00.230 --> 00:10:04.900
the quality of the players and
what the teams really need.

00:10:04.900 --> 00:10:07.680
And it's important for
players to identify themself,

00:10:07.680 --> 00:10:10.510
to know themself, and to
know what is their role

00:10:10.510 --> 00:10:12.180
and the responsibility
on the field.

00:10:12.180 --> 00:10:15.260
And when you have a talent
in the team and everybody

00:10:15.260 --> 00:10:19.800
respecting each other,
then you have more time

00:10:19.800 --> 00:10:23.174
to succeed and to be successful.

00:10:23.174 --> 00:10:25.340
And the French National
Team, that's was a strength.

00:10:25.340 --> 00:10:27.050
At Arsenal, that
was our strength.

00:10:27.050 --> 00:10:31.120
Thierry Henry knew
that his strength

00:10:31.120 --> 00:10:32.740
was to score the goals.

00:10:32.740 --> 00:10:35.700
His strength was to run
behind the back four.

00:10:35.700 --> 00:10:37.540
Zidane was the mind of our team.

00:10:37.540 --> 00:10:40.200
He was the creative players.

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:41.890
You have architect.

00:10:41.890 --> 00:10:44.360
And you have builders.

00:10:44.360 --> 00:10:47.955
So when the builders
try to be the architect,

00:10:47.955 --> 00:10:49.370
we're having a problem.

00:10:49.370 --> 00:10:52.330
And I think in every kind
of business, it's the same.

00:10:52.330 --> 00:10:56.240
And at Arsenal at the time, if
I was try to be the architect,

00:10:56.240 --> 00:10:58.006
then it will be a problem.

00:10:58.006 --> 00:10:59.880
JON JAKLITSCH: We talked
about this a little

00:10:59.880 --> 00:11:01.355
before we came on stage.

00:11:01.355 --> 00:11:05.420
But you were actually very
excited to come to Google

00:11:05.420 --> 00:11:07.660
to learn how we work
together and how

00:11:07.660 --> 00:11:09.560
we build great teams,
which is something

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:11.537
I thought was very interesting.

00:11:11.537 --> 00:11:13.620
Do you want to maybe talk
a little bit about that?

00:11:13.620 --> 00:11:14.970
PATRICK VIEIRA: Yeah, I find
it quite really interesting,

00:11:14.970 --> 00:11:16.591
because you are
international brand.

00:11:16.591 --> 00:11:18.340
And I think you have
people who are coming

00:11:18.340 --> 00:11:20.155
from all around the world.

00:11:20.155 --> 00:11:21.530
And it's quite
really interesting

00:11:21.530 --> 00:11:25.360
to see how you put in
this kind of differences

00:11:25.360 --> 00:11:27.412
together to be
really successful.

00:11:27.412 --> 00:11:29.620
And when you look at in a
dressing room in our world,

00:11:29.620 --> 00:11:30.995
in football, it's
quite the same.

00:11:30.995 --> 00:11:33.073
Because we have players
coming all around

00:11:33.073 --> 00:11:36.150
the world, different background.

00:11:36.150 --> 00:11:37.770
But the objective
still the same--

00:11:37.770 --> 00:11:43.360
how can we put our difference
on the side but working together

00:11:43.360 --> 00:11:44.820
to be successful?

00:11:44.820 --> 00:11:46.520
And what I find quite
really interesting

00:11:46.520 --> 00:11:49.240
is that when we came
inside the building,

00:11:49.240 --> 00:11:50.588
I find it quite really fresh.

00:11:50.588 --> 00:11:52.300
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:52.300 --> 00:11:54.520
There's colors everywhere.

00:11:54.520 --> 00:11:57.770
And I think what make it
really successful brand

00:11:57.770 --> 00:12:00.450
is the fact that when you
come in in the building,

00:12:00.450 --> 00:12:01.970
you want to stay
in the building.

00:12:01.970 --> 00:12:04.220
You want to work
in the building.

00:12:04.220 --> 00:12:05.782
It's a good place to be.

00:12:05.782 --> 00:12:06.990
I know that the food is free.

00:12:06.990 --> 00:12:08.073
That's one of the reasons.

00:12:08.073 --> 00:12:09.564
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:09.564 --> 00:12:10.500
 

00:12:10.500 --> 00:12:11.370
JON JAKLITSCH: I don't
know if you've heard.

00:12:11.370 --> 00:12:13.120
But we're hiring if
you want to work here.

00:12:13.120 --> 00:12:13.690
[LAUGHTER]

00:12:13.690 --> 00:12:14.580
PATRICK VIEIRA: Yeah.

00:12:14.580 --> 00:12:17.090
But it's true.

00:12:17.090 --> 00:12:19.290
It is really nice
place to spend time.

00:12:19.290 --> 00:12:22.460
Because you spend more time here
than at home with your family.

00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:24.700
And that is what we need
to create in our world,

00:12:24.700 --> 00:12:28.080
in football is we want
players to come and spend

00:12:28.080 --> 00:12:31.280
time in our office-- in
the office, you can say.

00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:32.670
We want players
to come and spend

00:12:32.670 --> 00:12:33.920
time in the training ground.

00:12:33.920 --> 00:12:39.610
So it's important for us to
make it nice, to make it really,

00:12:39.610 --> 00:12:41.100
really nice to spend time.

00:12:41.100 --> 00:12:43.840
And I find it-- I do
understand one of the reason

00:12:43.840 --> 00:12:45.390
that you guys been
really successful.

00:12:45.390 --> 00:12:48.400
And I think that is quite
really interesting for us

00:12:48.400 --> 00:12:50.469
to take back to our world.

00:12:50.469 --> 00:12:52.760
JON JAKLITSCH: And we hope
you can get some ideas when

00:12:52.760 --> 00:12:53.430
we do the tour.

00:12:53.430 --> 00:12:54.260
Have that later.

00:12:54.260 --> 00:12:54.760
Thanks.

00:12:54.760 --> 00:12:55.930
PATRICK VIEIRA: Yes.

00:12:55.930 --> 00:12:58.700
JON JAKLITSCH: Changing
subjects a little bit,

00:12:58.700 --> 00:13:01.230
still talking about
your playing career now,

00:13:01.230 --> 00:13:05.730
you've had the chance to captain
a few teams in your career.

00:13:05.730 --> 00:13:09.602
Tell me what it takes
to be a good captain.

00:13:09.602 --> 00:13:11.060
PATRICK VIEIRA: I
think it's always

00:13:11.060 --> 00:13:17.010
the same question is are
you born as a leader,

00:13:17.010 --> 00:13:19.830
or you become a leader?

00:13:19.830 --> 00:13:20.593
What do you think?

00:13:20.593 --> 00:13:21.519
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:13:21.519 --> 00:13:23.001
 

00:13:23.001 --> 00:13:23.834
PATRICK VIEIRA: Huh?

00:13:23.834 --> 00:13:25.690
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:25.690 --> 00:13:28.650
PATRICK VIEIRA: You
become a leader?

00:13:28.650 --> 00:13:29.250
I don't agree.

00:13:29.250 --> 00:13:31.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:31.700 --> 00:13:33.860
 

00:13:33.860 --> 00:13:35.610
But that is what is
interesting is that we

00:13:35.610 --> 00:13:37.540
have a different point of view.

00:13:37.540 --> 00:13:44.540
But with my experience is that
I believe that in football,

00:13:44.540 --> 00:13:47.830
to be successful, everybody
has to take leadership.

00:13:47.830 --> 00:13:50.997
We need 11 leader on the
field to be successful.

00:13:50.997 --> 00:13:53.572
 

00:13:53.572 --> 00:13:54.530
And it was quite funny.

00:13:54.530 --> 00:13:58.570
Because when I was spending
time in Manchester City,

00:13:58.570 --> 00:14:02.310
people will say that Mario
Balotelli is not a leader.

00:14:02.310 --> 00:14:04.310
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:04.310 --> 00:14:04.810
 

00:14:04.810 --> 00:14:05.760
But I disagree.

00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:08.440
I think he's a leader--
in a different way--

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:09.747
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:09.747 --> 00:14:10.830
--but he's still a leader.

00:14:10.830 --> 00:14:12.810
Just to give you an
example, we were playing

00:14:12.810 --> 00:14:15.330
the game against Tottenham.

00:14:15.330 --> 00:14:17.400
And we was losing two-nil.

00:14:17.400 --> 00:14:19.340
And we managed to
get back to the game.

00:14:19.340 --> 00:14:20.540
It was a two-two.

00:14:20.540 --> 00:14:24.410
And it was a last
minute penalty.

00:14:24.410 --> 00:14:28.150
To take that responsibility,
the last kick off the game,

00:14:28.150 --> 00:14:32.860
to take that responsibility,k
you have to be--

00:14:32.860 --> 00:14:33.757
--you understand?

00:14:33.757 --> 00:14:35.090
Your mind has to be a bit crazy.

00:14:35.090 --> 00:14:36.590
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:36.590 --> 00:14:38.440
But it's part of being a leader.

00:14:38.440 --> 00:14:41.210
 

00:14:41.210 --> 00:14:44.650
And for me, him taking the
ball in front of Sergio Aguero,

00:14:44.650 --> 00:14:46.590
put it, and then
scored the goal is

00:14:46.590 --> 00:14:49.280
for me is a sign of leadership.

00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:51.570
And then after,
you have this type

00:14:51.570 --> 00:14:54.300
of leader, what, like
Tony Adams at Arsenal.

00:14:54.300 --> 00:14:57.040
He was really vocal,
really strong.

00:14:57.040 --> 00:14:59.020
They didn't stop talking.

00:14:59.020 --> 00:15:02.270
And he was a proper leader.

00:15:02.270 --> 00:15:04.530
And I was a different
type of leader.

00:15:04.530 --> 00:15:07.500
I was more leading by example.

00:15:07.500 --> 00:15:11.050
The way that I will
conduct myself on the field

00:15:11.050 --> 00:15:16.500
wasn't really vocal,
but I was tackling.

00:15:16.500 --> 00:15:17.600
I was running.

00:15:17.600 --> 00:15:19.800
I was-- that is a different
type of leadership.

00:15:19.800 --> 00:15:21.920
So that's why I
believe that we all

00:15:21.920 --> 00:15:24.860
have a little bit of
leadership in ourself.

00:15:24.860 --> 00:15:28.435
And it's important
in any things that we

00:15:28.435 --> 00:15:32.896
are doing to show that
we are quite strong.

00:15:32.896 --> 00:15:35.020
JON JAKLITSCH: Did you
feel throughout your career

00:15:35.020 --> 00:15:38.380
that you ever had to adjust
your leadership style

00:15:38.380 --> 00:15:41.194
to match the people
you were working with?

00:15:41.194 --> 00:15:42.150
PATRICK VIEIRA: Um--

00:15:42.150 --> 00:15:43.983
JON JAKLITSCH: Or do
you feel the team kind

00:15:43.983 --> 00:15:46.080
of morphed more around the
captain and the leader?

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:47.621
PATRICK VIEIRA: I
think as a captain,

00:15:47.621 --> 00:15:50.630
I was always tried
to be a positive.

00:15:50.630 --> 00:15:53.260
 

00:15:53.260 --> 00:15:57.940
And it was important for me
was that, yes, I was a captain,

00:15:57.940 --> 00:16:02.530
but it doesn't give
me the right to make

00:16:02.530 --> 00:16:04.840
all the decision by myself.

00:16:04.840 --> 00:16:09.432
When I was at Arsenal, I was--
Dennis Bergkamp, Martin Keown,

00:16:09.432 --> 00:16:14.640
[INAUDIBLE], Seaman, or--
before making any decision,

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:17.440
I was talking to them, because
it was a team decision.

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:22.250
So they was really part of the
decision that I was making.

00:16:22.250 --> 00:16:25.176
Being a captain doesn't
give you the right

00:16:25.176 --> 00:16:27.320
to make the decision
by yourself.

00:16:27.320 --> 00:16:30.300
You have responsibility, but one
of the biggest responsibility

00:16:30.300 --> 00:16:31.610
is to bring everybody together.

00:16:31.610 --> 00:16:35.250
So making a decision
with other players

00:16:35.250 --> 00:16:41.730
I think give them a little
bit of captaincy as well.

00:16:41.730 --> 00:16:44.250
So it was important for
me to make them understand

00:16:44.250 --> 00:16:46.459
that captain is
just the hand band

00:16:46.459 --> 00:16:48.000
that you're putting
around your hand.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:54.712
But the team is more important
than just a captain on himself.

00:16:54.712 --> 00:16:55.920
JON JAKLITSCH: Great, great.

00:16:55.920 --> 00:17:00.770
Now sticking with the concept of
teammates, I'm curious to know,

00:17:00.770 --> 00:17:04.380
throughout your career, who do
you think the best player you

00:17:04.380 --> 00:17:05.880
played with throughout
your career--

00:17:05.880 --> 00:17:08.088
and I'm putting you on the
spot a little bit, I know.

00:17:08.088 --> 00:17:09.270
PATRICK VIEIRA: Yeah.

00:17:09.270 --> 00:17:11.520
But just to be
diplomat, I will say it.

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:13.740
What do you think
a good player is?

00:17:13.740 --> 00:17:14.240
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:14.240 --> 00:17:16.020
JON JAKLITSCH: Ooh, I'm
getting interviewed here.

00:17:16.020 --> 00:17:17.310
PATRICK VIEIRA: I'm just going
to test him a little bit.

00:17:17.310 --> 00:17:18.680
JON JAKLITSCH: I'm
going to change it back.

00:17:18.680 --> 00:17:20.324
I think it's someone who
listens to their captain.

00:17:20.324 --> 00:17:20.824
No--

00:17:20.824 --> 00:17:22.530
[LAUGHTER]

00:17:22.530 --> 00:17:25.890
I think-- and relating
this back to Google

00:17:25.890 --> 00:17:27.790
and what I think
we've seen internally,

00:17:27.790 --> 00:17:31.140
I think it's ability to
listen to your teammates,

00:17:31.140 --> 00:17:33.760
understand maybe what
some of their strengths

00:17:33.760 --> 00:17:35.820
are, what some of
their weaknesses are,

00:17:35.820 --> 00:17:37.940
and kind of play
into that, not trying

00:17:37.940 --> 00:17:41.880
to be someone else
that you're not,

00:17:41.880 --> 00:17:44.820
and sticking with your
core strengths as a person.

00:17:44.820 --> 00:17:48.790
But I think treating the
team above the individual

00:17:48.790 --> 00:17:49.950
is what I would say.

00:17:49.950 --> 00:17:50.932
PATRICK VIEIRA: Yeah.

00:17:50.932 --> 00:17:52.471
And completely,
I agree with you.

00:17:52.471 --> 00:17:54.220
And this is why when
people asking me that

00:17:54.220 --> 00:17:56.670
question, two names always up.

00:17:56.670 --> 00:18:00.730
One is Zinedine Zidane and the
other one is Dennis Bergkamp.

00:18:00.730 --> 00:18:03.690
And the reasons being
every single players

00:18:03.690 --> 00:18:09.000
who played around those
players has been fantastic.

00:18:09.000 --> 00:18:10.770
What I like about
both of them is

00:18:10.770 --> 00:18:16.100
that they're making the
people around look good.

00:18:16.100 --> 00:18:19.614
And for me, this is a sign
of a top class player.

00:18:19.614 --> 00:18:22.360
There's a lot of good
players, but there's just

00:18:22.360 --> 00:18:24.890
a little bit of top players.

00:18:24.890 --> 00:18:27.450
And for me, Zidane with
the French National Team--

00:18:27.450 --> 00:18:32.264
you can tell them-- Henri,
Berg-- Anelka, [INAUDIBLE],

00:18:32.264 --> 00:18:33.070
Dugarry.

00:18:33.070 --> 00:18:36.100
All those players who
played around Zidane

00:18:36.100 --> 00:18:38.770
expressed themselves
really well.

00:18:38.770 --> 00:18:41.095
And the same at Arnsenal--
Bergkamp played with Henri,

00:18:41.095 --> 00:18:43.670
played with Anelka,
Overmars, Pires.

00:18:43.670 --> 00:18:47.230
All those players look
really good because Bergkamp

00:18:47.230 --> 00:18:49.030
makes them look really good.

00:18:49.030 --> 00:18:54.190
So for me, this is a
sign of special players.

00:18:54.190 --> 00:18:56.590
JON JAKLITSCH: Now how
about the best player

00:18:56.590 --> 00:19:01.420
you think you played
against in your career?

00:19:01.420 --> 00:19:03.810
PATRICK VIEIRA: Against?

00:19:03.810 --> 00:19:07.659
I would say Roy
Keane from-- yes.

00:19:07.659 --> 00:19:09.575
JON JAKLITSCH: I thought
that would come out.

00:19:09.575 --> 00:19:12.170
 

00:19:12.170 --> 00:19:14.670
PATRICK VIEIRA: I would say Roy
Keane because-- because it's

00:19:14.670 --> 00:19:19.300
funny because we are sharing
the same type of vision

00:19:19.300 --> 00:19:21.440
of the game, of leadership.

00:19:21.440 --> 00:19:24.840
He has a really strong
mind, he's a fighter,

00:19:24.840 --> 00:19:29.050
he's a team player, and
he likes to compete,

00:19:29.050 --> 00:19:34.880
and he, as well, has a
psychology mind that he

00:19:34.880 --> 00:19:36.500
likes to use in the game.

00:19:36.500 --> 00:19:38.330
That, I quite like as well.

00:19:38.330 --> 00:19:42.160
So we are quite similar.

00:19:42.160 --> 00:19:45.770
And to be honest, every time
we play against each other,

00:19:45.770 --> 00:19:49.730
it was tough, it was
really difficult,

00:19:49.730 --> 00:19:51.800
and that's why I have a
massive respect for him

00:19:51.800 --> 00:19:54.968
because he's been
a fantastic player.

00:19:54.968 --> 00:19:56.360
JON JAKLITSCH: Great.

00:19:56.360 --> 00:20:00.490
Now let's switch over to
your managerial career now.

00:20:00.490 --> 00:20:03.830
You mentioned that if we asked
you, when you were younger,

00:20:03.830 --> 00:20:06.240
you would have said, no way
would I ever be a manager.

00:20:06.240 --> 00:20:07.200
So why now?

00:20:07.200 --> 00:20:12.000
And, I guess, what changed
since you were younger?

00:20:12.000 --> 00:20:15.164
PATRICK VIEIRA: I think
because I never put myself

00:20:15.164 --> 00:20:16.080
on the other the side.

00:20:16.080 --> 00:20:21.430
When I stopped playing
for Manchester City,

00:20:21.430 --> 00:20:23.480
I didn't really
know what I really

00:20:23.480 --> 00:20:26.540
wanted to do because I had been
playing football, and focused,

00:20:26.540 --> 00:20:31.060
and concentrating about
football for 15 to 17 years.

00:20:31.060 --> 00:20:33.960
So when I decided to stop,
it was really difficult

00:20:33.960 --> 00:20:37.199
for me to find my
way, I would say.

00:20:37.199 --> 00:20:39.240
So I was really lucky
because at Manchester City,

00:20:39.240 --> 00:20:44.380
there was one of the directors,
called Brian Marwood.

00:20:44.380 --> 00:20:46.680
And Brian had a vision
of me that I even

00:20:46.680 --> 00:20:48.290
didn't have for myself.

00:20:48.290 --> 00:20:50.840
So that's why it's
really important

00:20:50.840 --> 00:20:52.940
to believe and to
listen to people

00:20:52.940 --> 00:20:56.406
because sometimes people can
come with a really good idea.

00:20:56.406 --> 00:21:01.160
So Brian offered me
to spend two years

00:21:01.160 --> 00:21:04.790
in the staff in Manchester
City and to spend time

00:21:04.790 --> 00:21:07.260
in different departments
in the football club.

00:21:07.260 --> 00:21:09.362
I knew that I wanted to
stay involved in football

00:21:09.362 --> 00:21:11.570
because this is what I love,
and this is what I know,

00:21:11.570 --> 00:21:13.240
and this is what I do best.

00:21:13.240 --> 00:21:14.420
But in which department?

00:21:14.420 --> 00:21:15.690
I really didn't know at all.

00:21:15.690 --> 00:21:19.000
So I spent time in the Academy,
I spent time in the finance,

00:21:19.000 --> 00:21:21.720
I spent time with the
sporting director,

00:21:21.720 --> 00:21:28.060
I spent time in recruitment,
in the community.

00:21:28.060 --> 00:21:30.490
I tried to understand where
I can feel comfortable

00:21:30.490 --> 00:21:32.700
or where I can
bring my experience.

00:21:32.700 --> 00:21:35.660
And sitting in the
office wasn't something

00:21:35.660 --> 00:21:39.260
that I was feeling
really comfortable with.

00:21:39.260 --> 00:21:42.050
And when I spent time
in the Academy, the fact

00:21:42.050 --> 00:21:46.300
that spending time with
the young players--

00:21:46.300 --> 00:21:48.760
the way they were looking at
me, the way they were taking

00:21:48.760 --> 00:21:51.780
into consideration the
message I was sending to them,

00:21:51.780 --> 00:21:53.340
I felt really
comfortable about it.

00:21:53.340 --> 00:21:55.900
At the same time, I
was doing my badges.

00:21:55.900 --> 00:21:59.110
And I just fell in love because
I put myself in a situation

00:21:59.110 --> 00:22:00.670
that I never been before.

00:22:00.670 --> 00:22:05.400
And doing that allowed me
to know more about myself

00:22:05.400 --> 00:22:09.140
and I felt in love
with coaching.

00:22:09.140 --> 00:22:11.950
And I did my badges, and I
worked for two and half years

00:22:11.950 --> 00:22:16.772
with the under 21 in
Manchester City, and I love it.

00:22:16.772 --> 00:22:17.980
JON JAKLITSCH: That's great.

00:22:17.980 --> 00:22:18.521
That's great.

00:22:18.521 --> 00:22:19.980
And you've had a
chance, obviously,

00:22:19.980 --> 00:22:23.230
to play for a lot of great
managers over the years.

00:22:23.230 --> 00:22:25.520
Is there anyone in
particular that you feel

00:22:25.520 --> 00:22:27.390
like has influenced you most?

00:22:27.390 --> 00:22:29.534
Or do you think it's
a bit from each one?

00:22:29.534 --> 00:22:30.700
PATRICK VIEIRA: All of them.

00:22:30.700 --> 00:22:33.020
All of them because
I've been really lucky.

00:22:33.020 --> 00:22:36.400
I had some of the best
managers in the world.

00:22:36.400 --> 00:22:40.650
And I spent time with them,
I've been listening to them,

00:22:40.650 --> 00:22:47.440
and, of course, I'll take
a little bit of something

00:22:47.440 --> 00:22:49.210
off each one of them.

00:22:49.210 --> 00:22:54.110
Like Arsene Wenger--
spending nine years with him.

00:22:54.110 --> 00:23:00.440
The freedom that he gives to the
players, his calmness, the fact

00:23:00.440 --> 00:23:05.140
that this office is always
open for conversation, the way

00:23:05.140 --> 00:23:09.160
that he's managed
to turn your head

00:23:09.160 --> 00:23:11.040
around was really interesting.

00:23:11.040 --> 00:23:14.280
Because Arsene--
you can say, OK, I'm

00:23:14.280 --> 00:23:16.250
going to go to his office.

00:23:16.250 --> 00:23:18.140
I'm going to tell him
that he was wrong.

00:23:18.140 --> 00:23:21.400
You come back from his office
and you say, no, he was right.

00:23:21.400 --> 00:23:24.500
He was really good on
turning and changing people

00:23:24.500 --> 00:23:25.850
and players' minds.

00:23:25.850 --> 00:23:28.762
This is something that I
find really interesting.

00:23:28.762 --> 00:23:30.470
The fact that I spent
time with Mourinho,

00:23:30.470 --> 00:23:34.220
where he was really strict
and with a really clear idea

00:23:34.220 --> 00:23:36.940
about what he wants,
what he expects.

00:23:36.940 --> 00:23:40.450
The information he was
given to the players--

00:23:40.450 --> 00:23:43.570
that was really, really good.

00:23:43.570 --> 00:23:48.150
I had Capello when I was 18
years old, when I was in Italy.

00:23:48.150 --> 00:23:52.590
The way that he's
managing the group,

00:23:52.590 --> 00:23:55.070
his tactical knowledge--
I've been really lucky.

00:23:55.070 --> 00:23:58.840
So I learned a little
bit off of all of them.

00:23:58.840 --> 00:24:01.020
But I think what is
important and if I really

00:24:01.020 --> 00:24:05.330
want to be successful,
I have to know who I am.

00:24:05.330 --> 00:24:13.450
I have to coach with my
personality and my philosophy.

00:24:13.450 --> 00:24:17.560
If not-- if I try to be
Mourinho, Wenger, or Capello--

00:24:17.560 --> 00:24:21.684
I'm not going to have any
chance to be successful.

00:24:21.684 --> 00:24:23.850
JON JAKLITSCH: If we were
to ask your players today

00:24:23.850 --> 00:24:29.210
to describe you as a manager,
and you said, I need to be me--

00:24:29.210 --> 00:24:32.730
who are you as a manager?

00:24:32.730 --> 00:24:34.780
PATRICK VIEIRA: That's
a really good question.

00:24:34.780 --> 00:24:39.730
I think I am in the process
of learning who I am

00:24:39.730 --> 00:24:44.440
because I am a young manager.

00:24:44.440 --> 00:24:47.340
I spent two years
with a developing

00:24:47.340 --> 00:24:52.160
squad and a developing squad is
at a different level from where

00:24:52.160 --> 00:24:54.940
I am now-- because for
two years I was working

00:24:54.940 --> 00:24:56.720
with the development squad.

00:24:56.720 --> 00:24:58.730
And the developing
squad, winning or losing,

00:24:58.730 --> 00:24:59.479
it doesn't matter.

00:24:59.479 --> 00:25:02.830
What is important is to
develop players for the future.

00:25:02.830 --> 00:25:04.790
And now I went to
a different world

00:25:04.790 --> 00:25:08.070
where it is all about winning
and winning with style.

00:25:08.070 --> 00:25:10.780
And I'm facing some situations
that I've never been in before.

00:25:10.780 --> 00:25:14.120
And I'm in a certain
situation that I still

00:25:14.120 --> 00:25:16.850
learn a lot about myself--
how to deal with a situation,

00:25:16.850 --> 00:25:25.700
how to deal when we're losing
7-0 against the other team.

00:25:25.700 --> 00:25:28.510
That type of situation
makes me learn about myself,

00:25:28.510 --> 00:25:31.850
about how to deal with the
pressure because being a player

00:25:31.850 --> 00:25:34.050
and being a coach is
completely different.

00:25:34.050 --> 00:25:37.576
When I was a player, I was
concentrated about myself.

00:25:37.576 --> 00:25:39.270
Players, in general,
we are egoistic

00:25:39.270 --> 00:25:41.370
and we're always
thinking about ourselves.

00:25:41.370 --> 00:25:44.724
I was preparing myself
during the week to be fit,

00:25:44.724 --> 00:25:46.890
and to be mentally prepared,
and tactically prepared

00:25:46.890 --> 00:25:48.660
for the game on the weekend.

00:25:48.660 --> 00:25:51.780
And when you are a
coach, you become last.

00:25:51.780 --> 00:25:53.220
You're thinking
about other people

00:25:53.220 --> 00:25:54.700
before thinking about yourself.

00:25:54.700 --> 00:25:57.440
So the transition is
completely different.

00:25:57.440 --> 00:25:59.430
And the transition
was difficult.

00:25:59.430 --> 00:26:01.480
So I'm in the situation
that I'm still

00:26:01.480 --> 00:26:04.940
learning about myself and
knowing about myself, about who

00:26:04.940 --> 00:26:06.662
I am, as a coach.

00:26:06.662 --> 00:26:07.579
JON JAKLITSCH: Great.

00:26:07.579 --> 00:26:08.995
You also mentioned
that you wanted

00:26:08.995 --> 00:26:11.930
to bring your philosophy
towards the game-- kind of how

00:26:11.930 --> 00:26:13.780
you think about strategy.

00:26:13.780 --> 00:26:16.580
Can you tell us how you
think about strategy

00:26:16.580 --> 00:26:17.340
towards the game?

00:26:17.340 --> 00:26:19.887
And how you try to implement
that at New York City FC.

00:26:19.887 --> 00:26:20.720
PATRICK VIEIRA: Yes.

00:26:20.720 --> 00:26:22.930
I have a clear philosophy
and a clear way

00:26:22.930 --> 00:26:28.250
that I want to play in
position or out of position.

00:26:28.250 --> 00:26:30.560
We're watching the
opposition team.

00:26:30.560 --> 00:26:32.030
And then the way
we are preparing

00:26:32.030 --> 00:26:33.600
ourselves is that
we analyze what

00:26:33.600 --> 00:26:37.570
is the strength and the
weakness of the opposition team.

00:26:37.570 --> 00:26:39.420
And during the week,
we work on that.

00:26:39.420 --> 00:26:41.790
Normally, what we
are doing is we

00:26:41.790 --> 00:26:46.180
spent two days regarding
how can we really hurt them

00:26:46.180 --> 00:26:51.530
and two days about
how we can control

00:26:51.530 --> 00:26:53.080
the strength of the
opposition team--

00:26:53.080 --> 00:26:55.860
what to expect from
the opposition team.

00:26:55.860 --> 00:26:58.700
And then we get the time
where we focus on ourselves,

00:26:58.700 --> 00:27:03.440
about how can we improve from
one game to the other game.

00:27:03.440 --> 00:27:05.960
All the training that
we are doing is filmed.

00:27:05.960 --> 00:27:08.870
And then we do a lot of
videos before training,

00:27:08.870 --> 00:27:10.030
after training.

00:27:10.030 --> 00:27:14.360
Players do an individual meeting
with the coaches regarding

00:27:14.360 --> 00:27:18.290
the position because
what we find out

00:27:18.290 --> 00:27:21.720
is that some players are
really learning faster

00:27:21.720 --> 00:27:25.970
and the message is more clear
when they are on the field.

00:27:25.970 --> 00:27:31.420
And for other ones, it's
when they are in the room.

00:27:31.420 --> 00:27:34.010
And the game is really tactical.

00:27:34.010 --> 00:27:36.680
So that means it's
important for us

00:27:36.680 --> 00:27:38.900
to really spend time on
the tactical side of it

00:27:38.900 --> 00:27:42.200
because games can be
losing and winning

00:27:42.200 --> 00:27:44.965
in a tactical
aspect of the game.

00:27:44.965 --> 00:27:45.840
JON JAKLITSCH: Sure.

00:27:45.840 --> 00:27:50.090
And turning now to New York
City FC and kind of this season,

00:27:50.090 --> 00:27:52.960
obviously, you've set very
high expectations for the team,

