00:31:27.530 --> 00:31:29.667
in the US versus in Europe.

00:31:29.667 --> 00:31:31.500
What do you think the
biggest difference is?

00:31:31.500 --> 00:31:34.540
Obviously, soccer is
not the number one sport

00:31:34.540 --> 00:31:37.000
in the US versus Europe.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:40.290
Do you think it's just the
games aren't on TV as much?

00:31:40.290 --> 00:31:42.610
As you mentioned, there's
not as much grassroots.

00:31:42.610 --> 00:31:46.220
PATRICK VIEIRA: I think it's
a little bit of everything.

00:31:46.220 --> 00:31:48.624
When you're going
to college here,

00:31:48.624 --> 00:31:50.290
when you look at the
college competition

00:31:50.290 --> 00:31:55.700
here-- the football in college--
you're training twice a week

00:31:55.700 --> 00:31:58.680
and you play four
months of competition.

00:31:58.680 --> 00:32:04.340
And this is between
16, 17 to 22.

00:32:04.340 --> 00:32:10.190
And this is a crucial period
of your development in Europe.

00:32:10.190 --> 00:32:13.930
And that period--
this is where you

00:32:13.930 --> 00:32:17.980
make it or you don't
make it, in Europe.

00:32:17.980 --> 00:32:21.630
And to develop those
players, in the US,

00:32:21.630 --> 00:32:26.830
and that age gap is too late.

00:32:26.830 --> 00:32:28.620
And they will need
more coaches, they

00:32:28.620 --> 00:32:33.320
will need more
grassroots training,

00:32:33.320 --> 00:32:36.860
they will need more
facilities as well.

00:32:36.860 --> 00:32:41.090
But it will take another 20
to 30 years to be better.

00:32:41.090 --> 00:32:44.730
But I think they are doing
the right stuff at the moment

00:32:44.730 --> 00:32:50.670
because everywhere we're going,
there are fans at the stadium,

00:32:50.670 --> 00:32:52.830
there are kids who
are playing football.

00:32:52.830 --> 00:32:56.820
And I think the future looks
bright for the US National

00:32:56.820 --> 00:32:57.473
Team.

00:32:57.473 --> 00:32:58.200
JON JAKLITSCH: That's great.

