Or do you think that
will come sooner?

00:33:25.200 --> 00:33:27.190
What is it going to
take, essentially?

00:33:27.190 --> 00:33:28.940
PATRICK VIEIRA: I think
it will take time.

00:33:28.940 --> 00:33:34.380
It will take time because the
league is completely different.

00:33:34.380 --> 00:33:37.920
I'll just give you an example--
we played in Portland.

00:33:37.920 --> 00:33:40.280
From New York to Portland
is seven hours-- six hours

00:33:40.280 --> 00:33:42.300
and a half, seven hours flight.

00:33:42.300 --> 00:33:44.290
When you're in
Europe, six, seven

00:33:44.290 --> 00:33:47.690
hours is the period you're
taking to go to holiday.

00:33:47.690 --> 00:33:50.860
So you're not traveling six,
seven hours to play football.

00:33:50.860 --> 00:33:54.670
So the traveling is a
massive problem in the MLS.

00:33:54.670 --> 00:33:56.470
And you have to deal with it.

00:33:56.470 --> 00:34:00.850
So you have some
problems in the US

00:34:00.850 --> 00:34:02.740
that you don't have in Europe.

00:34:02.740 --> 00:34:04.790
So they just need to
find the right way

00:34:04.790 --> 00:34:09.880
to deal with those issues and
I think things will be OK.

00:34:09.880 --> 00:34:11.770
But I'm not worried
at all about it

00:34:11.770 --> 00:34:16.150
because when you look at
where soccer was 10 years ago

00:34:16.150 --> 00:34:19.510
and where it is now,
in the next 10 years,

00:34:19.510 --> 00:34:21.052
it will be even in
a different level.

00:34:21.052 --> 00:34:21.926
JON JAKLITSCH: Yeah.

00:34:21.926 --> 00:34:23.489
And then even in
the last five years,

00:34:23.489 --> 00:34:25.322
I've noticed a huge
difference in the number

00:34:25.322 --> 00:34:28.179
of people who are interested
in the World Cup, MLS.

00:34:28.179 --> 00:34:29.600
