PATRICK VIEIRA: The game
changed and I don't think

00:37:33.900 --> 00:37:35.960
the game changed for good.

00:37:35.960 --> 00:37:39.690
I think, honestly, it
became a little bit more

00:37:39.690 --> 00:37:43.310
difficult because I believe
that the gap is going up

00:37:43.310 --> 00:37:45.660
between fans and players.

00:37:45.660 --> 00:37:50.880
And one of the reasons being is
that young players, I believe,

00:37:50.880 --> 00:37:56.540
today are earning
too much, too early

00:37:56.540 --> 00:37:58.930
with not showing too much.

00:37:58.930 --> 00:38:01.554
And this is what the
problem is in football.

00:38:01.554 --> 00:38:03.220
But I don't think
it's just in football,

00:38:03.220 --> 00:38:06.890
I think it's a problem that
we are facing in our society.

00:38:06.890 --> 00:38:12.520
Young players or a young
person wants the job

00:38:12.520 --> 00:38:16.180
with doing nothing.

00:38:16.180 --> 00:38:18.590
And this is a problem
of the society.

00:38:18.590 --> 00:38:21.210
And this is what we
have to deal with.

00:38:21.210 --> 00:38:23.800
And I think clubs--
we have a massive part

00:38:23.800 --> 00:38:28.550
to play because
to earn something,

00:38:28.550 --> 00:38:32.120
you need to deserve it,
you need to work for it.

00:38:32.120 --> 00:38:33.570
And we need to change that.

00:38:33.570 --> 00:38:36.980
If not, I believe that it
will get worse and worse.

00:38:36.980 --> 00:38:43.620
And if I'm 18
again and if I have

00:38:43.620 --> 00:38:47.100
to choose a manager that
I would like to play for,

00:38:47.100 --> 00:38:50.620
I would say Pep Guardiola
because of the vision

00:38:50.620 --> 00:38:53.496
that he had and the way
that his team is playing.

00:38:53.496 --> 00:38:56.410
 

00:38:56.410 --> 00:38:58.419
I think I would enjoy it.

00:38:58.419 --> 00:38:58.960
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:38:58.960 --> 00:38:59.740
Cool.

00:38:59.740 --> 00:39:00.320
Thank you.

00:39:00.320 --> 00:39:01.420
PATRICK VIEIRA: Thank you.

00:39:01.420 --> 00:39:03.628
JON JAKLITSCH: Let's take
a question from over here.

00:39:03.628 --> 00:39:04.950
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:39:04.950 --> 00:39:07.604
So you mentioned earlier
the greatest players

00:39:07.604 --> 00:39:08.270
you played with.

00:39:08.270 --> 00:39:15.250
And, obviously, the level of
top quality is unbelievable.

00:39:15.250 --> 00:39:18.140
I have two questions
that relate to that.

00:39:18.140 --> 00:39:22.210
One, how do you think is the
best way for those players

00:39:22.210 --> 00:39:23.840
to come here?

00:39:23.840 --> 00:39:26.200
At they start or in the
middle of their career,

00:39:26.200 --> 00:39:28.150
as opposed to what we've
seen over the course

00:39:28.150 --> 00:39:30.880
of the past decade, where
the top players come here

00:39:30.880 --> 00:39:32.580
towards the end of their career?

00:39:32.580 --> 00:39:37.600
And two, how has your
transition been here,

00:39:37.600 --> 00:39:41.420
given that you've played
on the highest of levels

00:39:41.420 --> 00:39:44.390
and you've come here,
where it's probably not

00:39:44.390 --> 00:39:45.962
on that same level?

00:39:45.962 --> 00:39:47.920
PATRICK VIEIRA: You're
asking me that question.

00:39:47.920 --> 00:39:49.380
You want to be in trouble
with the [INAUDIBLE]

00:39:49.380 --> 00:39:50.646
we have in our team?

00:39:50.646 --> 00:39:52.574
JON JAKLITSCH: Tough question.

00:39:52.574 --> 00:39:54.240
PATRICK VIEIRA: That's
a tough question.

00:39:54.240 --> 00:40:01.312
No, but I think you have--
I'll try to be a diplomat here.

00:40:01.312 --> 00:40:02.270
AUDIENCE: Please don't.

00:40:02.270 --> 00:40:05.190
 

00:40:05.190 --> 00:40:06.830
PATRICK VIEIRA:
You have stepped--

00:40:06.830 --> 00:40:07.954
you understand what I mean?

00:40:07.954 --> 00:40:11.190
You have, step by step--
I think when they created

00:40:11.190 --> 00:40:14.670
the MLS, what was really
important for the people

00:40:14.670 --> 00:40:18.640
from the MLS is, how
can we show to the world

00:40:18.640 --> 00:40:25.340
that we want to build a
really successful league?

00:40:25.340 --> 00:40:26.980
And I believe that
the first step

00:40:26.980 --> 00:40:30.180
was to bring players
with a big name

00:40:30.180 --> 00:40:33.040
because you want to make
the world aware of what

00:40:33.040 --> 00:40:34.420
we're trying to do here.

00:40:34.420 --> 00:40:36.900
And you're going to
a different step.

00:40:36.900 --> 00:40:39.310
And I think, in our football
club, it was the same.

00:40:39.310 --> 00:40:43.050
We bring players who were
marginally well known,

00:40:43.050 --> 00:40:47.050
but we bring players to
our football club who

00:40:47.050 --> 00:40:50.045
won everything in
Europe, but they still

00:40:50.045 --> 00:40:53.090
have desire to compete,
to be successful,

00:40:53.090 --> 00:40:56.620
and to win something
with the club.

00:40:56.620 --> 00:41:00.500
And I think, in the
next four, five years,

00:41:00.500 --> 00:41:03.320
the MLS has to move
to a different level.

00:41:03.320 --> 00:41:07.970
A different level is to
bring young, talented players

00:41:07.970 --> 00:41:08.860
from Europe.

00:41:08.860 --> 00:41:11.720
And I think Giovinco
is a perfect example.

00:41:11.720 --> 00:41:14.990
But before you bring in
these young talented players

00:41:14.990 --> 00:41:21.520
from Europe, you have to be
established as one of the best

00:41:21.520 --> 00:41:23.810
leagues in the world.

00:41:23.810 --> 00:41:27.140
And I don't think
the MLS is there yet.

00:41:27.140 --> 00:41:32.180
And to bring these young players
to the US is really difficult.

00:41:32.180 --> 00:41:36.195
Because when you are 21 years
old, you've played in Europe

00:41:36.195 --> 00:41:40.480
and you're still hoping to
play in your national team.

00:41:40.480 --> 00:41:43.080
And the best way to go
to the national team

00:41:43.080 --> 00:41:44.970
is to play for
the European team.

00:41:44.970 --> 00:41:48.720
And I think, as a nation here--
US-- we are not there yet.

00:41:48.720 --> 00:41:52.520
So it's really
difficult to convince

00:41:52.520 --> 00:41:55.540
because we don't have
all the tools yet

00:41:55.540 --> 00:42:01.460
to change the mind of
a 21 year old player

00:42:01.460 --> 00:42:02.910
to come to play in the US.

00:42:02.910 --> 00:42:06.060
And that will happen, I believe,
in the next five to 10 years.

00:42:06.060 --> 00:42:08.342
 

00:42:08.342 --> 00:42:09.050
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:42:09.050 --> 00:42:10.022
JON JAKLITSCH: Great.

00:42:10.022 --> 00:42:10.897
PATRICK VIEIRA: Yeah.

00:42:10.897 --> 00:42:12.734
I hope I answered your question.

00:42:12.734 --> 00:42:13.485
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:42:13.485 --> 00:42:14.110
Thanks so much.

00:42:14.110 --> 00:42:14.830
PATRICK VIEIRA: Thank you.

00:42:14.830 --> 00:42:15.830
JON JAKLITSCH: Next question.

00:42:15.830 --> 00:42:16.371
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:42:16.371 --> 00:42:19.793
I'm a huge fan, and I
really respect your work,

00:42:19.793 --> 00:42:22.108
and I think you're
an amazing player.

00:42:22.108 --> 00:42:24.640
So you had a very
interesting point

00:42:24.640 --> 00:42:30.240
when you mentioned
the team in 1998,

00:42:30.240 --> 00:42:35.740
where you said it was
representing the society.

00:42:35.740 --> 00:42:38.730
And you really sent
a clear message,

00:42:38.730 --> 00:42:41.786
saying that, hey,
even though we come

00:42:41.786 --> 00:42:46.670
from different backgrounds, we
are here together, as a team.

00:42:46.670 --> 00:42:49.510
So I guess my first
question is, do you

00:42:49.510 --> 00:42:55.630
think this is still true
with the current French team?

00:42:55.630 --> 00:42:59.609
Like for instance, Benzema
not being chosen and attacking

00:42:59.609 --> 00:43:00.400
the coach for that.

00:43:00.400 --> 00:43:02.815
PATRICK VIEIRA: You are trouble.

00:43:02.815 --> 00:43:05.713
You are trouble.

00:43:05.713 --> 00:43:10.750
AUDIENCE: So what do you
think is the secret recipe

00:43:10.750 --> 00:43:17.019
to make a team, like to
have all the players as one?

00:43:17.019 --> 00:43:19.263
And my last question
is, who do you think

00:43:19.263 --> 00:43:20.471
is going to win the Euro Cup?

00:43:20.471 --> 00:43:22.018
 

00:43:22.018 --> 00:43:23.393
PATRICK VIEIRA:
I think I'm going

00:43:23.393 --> 00:43:25.940
to start by answering
the second question.

00:43:25.940 --> 00:43:28.070
I hope France will
win the Euros.

00:43:28.070 --> 00:43:31.950
And I think they will
have a massive chance

00:43:31.950 --> 00:43:35.310
to win it because of the
young, talented player

00:43:35.310 --> 00:43:36.640
they have in the team.

00:43:36.640 --> 00:43:39.310
And, of course, in all
the big competitions,

00:43:39.310 --> 00:43:42.250
if you want to have a chance
of winning the competition,

00:43:42.250 --> 00:43:46.520
your best player has to be
at the peak of the game.

00:43:46.520 --> 00:43:51.620
So for France to win the Euros,
Pogba has to be at his best,

00:43:51.620 --> 00:43:55.180
Griezmann has to be at his
best, the goalkeeper, Lloris,

00:43:55.180 --> 00:43:58.880
has to be at his best,
and all the other players

00:43:58.880 --> 00:44:00.400
have to perform as well.

00:44:00.400 --> 00:44:02.250
But you are not going
to win a competition

00:44:02.250 --> 00:44:06.300
if your best players are
not at the best level.

00:44:06.300 --> 00:44:08.820
So hopefully, they
will be at their best,

00:44:08.820 --> 00:44:13.700
so they can have a chance
of winning the Euros.

00:44:13.700 --> 00:44:18.470
Answering your
first question-- I

00:44:18.470 --> 00:44:22.180
don't think-- knowing
Didier Deschamps the way

00:44:22.180 --> 00:44:29.865
that I know him,
he didn't pick up

00:44:29.865 --> 00:44:34.950
Benzema or Ben Arfa because
there wasn't a space for them

00:44:34.950 --> 00:44:36.030
in the national team.

00:44:36.030 --> 00:44:39.370
And I strongly believe
that it's based on what

00:44:39.370 --> 00:44:41.220
they are doing on the field.

00:44:41.220 --> 00:44:43.710
And then we can all agree,
saying, yeah, but he's good,

00:44:43.710 --> 00:44:45.270
he's not good.

00:44:45.270 --> 00:44:48.720
But what is important
for the people

00:44:48.720 --> 00:44:52.630
to understand is that
you are choosing people

00:44:52.630 --> 00:44:56.300
and you are making the team
not just for what's going on

00:44:56.300 --> 00:44:58.600
on the field, you're
making the team

00:44:58.600 --> 00:45:02.770
regarding, as well, how
they're going to live together

00:45:02.770 --> 00:45:05.450
and how they're going to
conduct themselves together.

00:45:05.450 --> 00:45:08.270
And Didier Deschamps was
the captain of the '98

00:45:08.270 --> 00:45:13.230
and was the captain of
the European Championship.

00:45:13.230 --> 00:45:18.414
And he managed, at that period,
to bring everybody together

00:45:18.414 --> 00:45:19.580
in the French National Team.

00:45:19.580 --> 00:45:24.940
So he knows what it takes
to win a competition.

00:45:24.940 --> 00:45:29.720
And if he makes that decision,
that is the best for the team

00:45:29.720 --> 00:45:33.230
because you're not just
playing-- you live together.

00:45:33.230 --> 00:45:36.720
And sometimes you have to make
a tough decision not just based

00:45:36.720 --> 00:45:40.030
on the football aspect
of it, but the outside

00:45:40.030 --> 00:45:42.652
is as important as what's
going on on the field.

00:45:42.652 --> 00:45:43.610
JON JAKLITSCH: Thanks.

00:45:43.610 --> 00:45:44.590
For you.

00:45:44.590 --> 00:45:47.802
AUDIENCE: So as an athlete, when
you're struggling on the pitch,

00:45:47.802 --> 00:45:49.510
or when you were
struggling on the pitch,

00:45:49.510 --> 00:45:51.170
or when your players
are now struggling

00:45:51.170 --> 00:45:54.080
and they make a mistake
or two mistakes, what do

00:45:54.080 --> 00:45:57.380
you do, or teach to do,
so that they successfully

00:45:57.380 --> 00:46:00.180
forget about it, and they're
able to focus on the next play,

00:46:00.180 --> 00:46:04.622
and able to perform, mid-match,
so that they can still perform

00:46:04.622 --> 00:46:06.205
well, even after
making a few mistakes

00:46:06.205 --> 00:46:07.434
and stay mentally tough?

00:46:07.434 --> 00:46:11.831
 

00:46:11.831 --> 00:46:13.330
PATRICK VIEIRA: The
best coach I had

00:46:13.330 --> 00:46:15.440
for that was Arsene
Wenger because I remember,

00:46:15.440 --> 00:46:19.130
when I was at Arsenal,
I made a few mistakes.

00:46:19.130 --> 00:46:21.780
 

00:46:21.780 --> 00:46:23.980
One of the actions
coming in my mind,

00:46:23.980 --> 00:46:27.100
it was when we were playing
the semifinal of the FA

00:46:27.100 --> 00:46:29.752
Cup against United
where I missed the pass,

00:46:29.752 --> 00:46:31.960
and the guy got the ball,
played it forward to Giggs,

00:46:31.960 --> 00:46:34.726
and Giggs scored.

00:46:34.726 --> 00:46:36.600
Before that game, I was
making a few mistakes

00:46:36.600 --> 00:46:39.182
and we could see the
goal straight away.

00:46:39.182 --> 00:46:41.140
But what was really
important-- and the message

00:46:41.140 --> 00:46:47.080
was from Arsene to me-- was
keep doing what you believe

00:46:47.080 --> 00:46:49.980
is right for the game.

00:46:49.980 --> 00:46:52.420
And that, for me,
was really important

00:46:52.420 --> 00:46:57.110
because it wasn't about-- it
was a technical mistake that I

00:46:57.110 --> 00:47:00.780
made, but the ideas
behind it were right.

00:47:00.780 --> 00:47:03.297
And that message, for
me, was really strong

00:47:03.297 --> 00:47:04.880
because that gave
me confidence that I

00:47:04.880 --> 00:47:05.963
was doing the right thing.

00:47:05.963 --> 00:47:09.140
So in training, of course,
I needed to practice more

00:47:09.140 --> 00:47:12.160
about this range of passes.

00:47:12.160 --> 00:47:13.880
And that really
gave me confidence

00:47:13.880 --> 00:47:17.130
to try it again and try it
again until I became successful

00:47:17.130 --> 00:47:18.520
on that.

00:47:18.520 --> 00:47:21.840
And that is a message that I've
tried to send to the players--

00:47:21.840 --> 00:47:24.490
mistakes are part of the game.

00:47:24.490 --> 00:47:26.270
Mistakes are part of the game.

00:47:26.270 --> 00:47:30.730
And I want them to
try to do it, if this

00:47:30.730 --> 00:47:35.540
is what the game was required,
if that was the right play

00:47:35.540 --> 00:47:36.500
to do.

00:47:36.500 --> 00:47:41.330
And, of course, what we're
doing in New York is,

00:47:41.330 --> 00:47:44.600
regarding the
period of the week,

00:47:44.600 --> 00:47:48.020
we're doing some
individual training.

00:47:48.020 --> 00:47:51.630
And we have five or six coaches.

00:47:51.630 --> 00:47:54.710
And we always take three,
four players and we

00:47:54.710 --> 00:47:59.256
make them work on their
weakness or their strength--

00:47:59.256 --> 00:48:00.380
it's dependent on the week.

00:48:00.380 --> 00:48:02.770
And we make them practice,
and practice, and practice.

00:48:02.770 --> 00:48:05.260
Because I strongly believe
the more you practice,

00:48:05.260 --> 00:48:07.377
the less mistakes you're making.

00:48:07.377 --> 00:48:08.210
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:48:08.210 --> 00:48:09.293
PATRICK VIEIRA: Thank you.

00:48:09.293 --> 00:48:11.464
 

00:48:11.464 --> 00:48:13.460
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:48:13.460 --> 00:48:15.320
So thank you for being here.

00:48:15.320 --> 00:48:18.154
And you named the best
players you played with.

00:48:18.154 --> 00:48:20.300
You said Zidane,
